<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-458-798  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 458 798.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  May 21 1990 n468 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Execs present trade ideas; government officials demand moredetails from policy group. (Computer Systems Policy Project)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Stacey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Computer Systems Policy Project, a group of 11 CEOsrepresenting the US computer industry, has proposed thatanti-dumping duties be suspended by the Department of Commerce onproducts that are in short supply.andP;  Government officials voicedskepticism over the proposal claiming that dumping results inshort supply situations and that suspending the duties would onlyworsen the situation.andP;  Other proposals being discussed includeletting foreign companies adopt a forward pricing methodology thatwould result in goods being priced below the average cost ofproduction for a start-up period.andP;  Capital and researchdevelopment costs would be spread over a product's full life.andP;  Theindustry group expects to meet in Jun 1990 to further elaborate onits proposals.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Political IssuesForeign CompetitionInternational TradeComputer IndustryGovernment RegulationUnited States. Department of CommerceComputer Systems Policy ProjectTrade and Professional AssociationsTariff.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>